- 'Total market capitalization' is the sum of the market capitalization of all companies within an industry;
- 'Average revenue' is the mean revenue of companies within an industry;
- 'Average total market capitalization' is the mean of the total market capitalization across all industries.

- The "forest of the corporate world" refers to the hierarchical structure of companies within industries and sectors;
- "Branches of industry and sub-industry" refer to the parent-child relationships in the industry hierarchy;
- "Cumulative wealth of its sector" refers to the cumulative total revenue of companies within the same sector.

- "Industries" can be metaphorically compared to ecosystems, and "companies" to species within those ecosystems;
- "Most populous" refers to the industries with the highest number of companies;
- "Top 10" indicates the first ten results in the ordered list.

- Market capitalization is a measure of a company's value, calculated by multiplying the number of outstanding shares by the current stock price.;
- 'None' in the context of market capitalization often indicates missing or invalid data.;
